sec.p:
Molecular excitons (electron–hole pairs with sizable binding energy) in porphyrin-based MOFs can efficiently migrate to new sites before recombining via radiative and/or non-radiative processes including exciton splitting into charge carriers. In pure-linker systems, exciton migration involves a self-exchange-type hopping process, which has been described via the Förster or Dexter mechanism depending on the spin manifold of the excited population. Even though singlet excitons are short-lived, the Förster resonance energy transfer (FRET) process is highly efficient (seen in natural light-harvesting complexes in photosystem I/II) to facilitate a long-range exciton migration (i.e. >50 nm). The FRET rate constant (kFRET = 2πJ²Θ/ħ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
